*****************************************************************************
*
*                    MeasTCM (MEASURE to TCM interface)
*                    ----------------------------------
*
* MeasTCM is the software component of the TCM                       )
* toolkit that provides the interface between measurement data on the
* HP host and the capacity planning tool TCM on the workstation.
*
* For more information, refer to the "TCM User's Guide and Reference
* Manual" (P/N 065084).
*
*
* History
* -------
*
* 13MAR92 > C31 NPV, first version written in COBOL85.
*           This version runs on Guardian 90 C20 or higher and supports
*           measurement data files with versions C10 (unofficialy), C20,
*           C30, D00, D10.
*
* 30OCT92   AAA IPM.
*
*         > Para 1000-INITIALIZE: the sort parameter NOWAIT-IO is now
*           specified.
*
*         > W08, W09, W13, and W14 didn't include internal disc activity;
*           this has been corrected.
*
*         > W13 and W14 didn't include explicit seek activity; this has
*           been corrected.
*
*         > During report print, when the first item on a new page happened
*           to be a category total, it was omitted. Also, the cpu busy
*           counter would not be reset to zero before starting with a new
*           category.
*
*         > The limit of 256 occurences of the same PID has been raised to
*           32768.
*
*         > The limit of 5000 processes per system has been raised to 20000.
*
*         > The sort of SYSTEM-TABLE has been removed. This is because the
*           sort processes messes up the link between the index into this
*           table and MEASURE-SYSTEM-NUMBER. This should be redesigned
*           eventually.
*
*         > A new control file parameter CPUPOWER has been added. It allows
*           to override the default CPU power values in CPU-TYPE-POWER.
*           This also resulted in the addition of two new messages,
*           77 and 78.
*
* 01JUN93 > Support for generation of multiple CSV data files included.
*           3000-CORE-PROCESSING loops through the entire process of CSV
*           generation for the number of CSV files. Opening the Spooler file
*           if specified, is done before this loop, and closed at the end
*           along with the Measure files.
*
*         > A new control file parameter NUMCSVS is added. This allows the
*           user to specify the number of CSV data files to be generated.
*           If it is not possible to generate the user specified number of
*           CSV data files, the maximum possible are generated.
*
*         > MEASURE-TABLE now includes the start and stop times and the
*           collection interval of the file.
*
*         > Validation of Measure data files to check if their time ranges
*           overlap has been included. If the Measure data file does not
*           have a specified collection interval, it is set as the
*           difference between the stop and start times of the file.
*
*         > CSVHI and CSVLO parameters are now optional. The time window of
*           each CSV data file produced is the "actual" time, i.e., the
*           start time is max(CSVLO, earliest start time) and stop time is
*           min(CSVHI, latest stop time). As far as is possible, CSV data
*           file with all zeroes will not be generated.
*
*         > Fixed algorithm to calculate the number of drives.
*
*         > Fixed the method by which the physical count of CPUs was being
*           calculated. This was not a reported problem.
*
*         > Support for D20 version of Measure data included. This program
*           also runs on D20 CISC and D20 RISC versions of Guardian 90.
*
*         > The audit report now prints out the details of each of the CSV
*           data files produced. The name of the CSV data file is also
*           printed in the heading.
*
*         > A "Run Summary" is also generated by this program. It is
*           displayed at the end of the run, and also at the end of the
*           audit report, if specified.
*
*         > The CSVDATA keyword in the control file is now used differently.
*           A maximum of five characters of the file name specified is used
*           to prefix the CSV data file. For eg., if the parameter is ABCDE
*           or ABCDEF, the CSV data file will be named ABCDE001, and so on.
*           If the parameter is ABCD, the CSV data file will be ABCD001.
*
* 15OCT93 IPM AAB - for Himalaya - altered the cpu-type-power table so that
*           NSR-N is found before NSR-M - both are type 7.  It is expected
*           that NSR-M types will not be released.
*           Chris Narrows.
*
* 17DEC93 IPM AAC - Chris Barrows.
*
*         > Added two new fields to the process workload CSV records.
*           TNSR-BUSY-TIME (secs) and ACCEL-BUSY-TIME (secs).
*           Columns 22 and 23.  These fields only applied to D20 so
*           considerable source restructoring was performed to allow
*           exception processing for each OS version.  The longest CSV
*           record was increased from 116 to 138 bytes.  For pre-D20
*           releases the two new fields will be empty (spaces).  For
*           data from multiple systems with mixed OS versions where one
*           is from D20 then the fields will be present or zero.
*
*           The increased record size of 138 exceeds the IXF default size
*           of 132, this means that (REC 138) must be included on all
*           uses of IXF if these new fields are not empty.  If this
*           IXF option is not included then TCM will be able to detect
*           the truncated data and issue and error message.
*
*         > Corrected a problem with NUMCSVS.  When * was specified and the
*           measurement was slightly longer than a multiple of intervals
*           then a final CSV file could be generated that was so small
*           that COBOL arithmetic overflow errors would occur.  The fix
*           was to ignore the residual time and set maximum CSVs to the
*           maximum number of whole intervals.
*
*         > Source re-structured in preparation for converting MEASTCM
*           to a TPDC client.  Changes gave 20% performance improvement.
*           Changes included -
*
*           1. Adding white space (blank lines) between comment lines
*              and source to make source more readable.
*
*           2. Upshifting all source statements excepts comments or literals.
*
*           3. Introduced block structuring, e.g.
*                  Removed all GO TO constructs.
*                  Removed all PERFORM ... THRU... constructs.
*                  Removed all complex nested IF statements and replaced
*                      with simple EVALUATE Statements.
*
*           4. Removed all complex and long in line PERFORM and IF constructs
*                  and replaced with performed paragraphs.
*
*           5. Included consistency with scope terminators. e.g. END-IF.
*
*           6. Added hyphen lines to seperate paragraphs (readability).
*
*           7. Added index to paragrpahs.
*
*         > Code added to support NSR-M processor type.  This was type 7
*           subtype 1.  Because of the use of subtypes nearly the whole
*           mechanism for assigning CPU POWER values was re-written.
*           Essentially the CPU-POWER table was ammended to include
*           subtypes for all CPU types.  This enabled a simplification
*           for dealing with CLX cpu types.  The CLXTYPE parameter now
*           simply establishes the appropriate subtype, so that all
*           remaining code simply uses the power table but specifies both
*           type and subtype. A new paragraph 3137-GET-CPU-TYPE-SUBTYPE
*           assigns the correct type and subtype to any cpu from any OS
*           version.
*
*         > CPU power conversion factor for NSR-N changed from 9.6 to 15.6,
*           NSR-L (C release) changed from 5.3 to 5.6.
*
*         > Fix for TPR 931026-1911-717 Incorrect VPROC.
*
*         > Fix for TPR 931025-1738-717 No SAVEABEND on object.
*
*         > Earliest START-TIME was not calculated correctly.  It was always
*           set to the START TIME of the first measure file.  It is now
*           set to the lowest start time of all measure files.
*
*         > re-wrote the mechanism for dealing with the CPU POWER
*           table.  This had to be changed to include D series
*           performance values as well as C series.  All references
*           now need to know the Guardian release before access.
*
*         > The CPUFACTOR command was changed to allow a reference
*           to the Guardian release.
*
*         > The CONVERTTO command was altered to allow conversion to
*           C or D specifically.  This is undocumented and will only
*           operate under debug-mode (SWITCH-15 ON).
*
*         > Introduced new completion message 86.  Generated if not
*           all CPUs have been measured and CONVERTTO is used.
*
*         > Added new flag - ABEND-REQUIRED-FLAG.  The default value
*           is zero (do not abend).  This is set to 1 prior to calling
*           9000-COMPLETION, when a saveabend file is required.  The
*           will now always terminate with a 0 termination status unless
*           a SAVEABEND file is required.
*
*         > Corrected spelling of tabel to table in COMPLETION msg 54.
*
* 15AUG94 IPM AAD - Jack Driscoll.
*
*         > Fix for TPR 94XXXX-XXXX-18106 does not work with measure d25
*           due to increased lengths of CPU and PROCESS entity records.
*           The D25 Measure was part of the D20.02 release and found
*           a gaping hole in our procedures.
*
* 12SEP94 IPM AAE - Chris Barrows.
*
*         > Included support for D30.
*
* 24FEB95 IPM AAF - Chris Barrows
*
*         > Increased variable TEMP-COLL-INT from Z(4) to Z(5).
*           The preceding filler loses its trailing space to compensate.
*           The is to correct the TPR S940830-1539-1980 Arith Overflow.
*
*         > Changed the version of C31 in the completion info to D30.
*           See TPR 941011-1514-717.
*
*         > Arithmetic overflow has been reported several times when
*           the DISC-TO-DOPN-READ-RATIO or DISC-TO-DOPN-WRITE-RATIO
*           exceeded their maximum values of 9(4).9(5).
*           These two fields have been increased in size to 9(9).9(5)
*           and ON SIZE ERROR clauses added to their source calculations.
*           If a size error occurs then the maximum value is used.
*           These fields affect the results of the process category
*           fields: W13 and W08 (for physical disc reads) and
*           W14 and W09 (for physical disc writes).
*
*         > Added new processor types to CPU POWER table.  These
*           are for the NSR-P and NSR-K.
*
*         > Increased the PROCESS-CEILING value from 20000 to 90000.
*
* 09OCT95 IPM AAG - Chris Barrows.
*
*         > Included support for D40.
*
* 20DEC95 IPM AAH - Chris Barrows. This IPM was never released.
*
*         > Included support for the Q (query) transaction type.
*           Only changed the VALID-TRANSACTION-TYPES values to include Q.
*
* 15APR96 NPV D40 - Chris Barrows.
*
*         > An NPV release for the aborted D20 AAH IPM.
*           Renamed the source file MEASTCMS to SOURCE1.
*           Added 3 more spare source modules Source2, 3, and 4.
*
* 21OCT96 IPM AAH - Guy Groulx.
*
*         > Fix for TPR 960517-1024-3333.  Overflow on LCM.
*         > Fix for TPR 930323-1200-10543.  Don't abend on entity errors,
*              an overflow count is now kept instead and warning displayed
*              on termination.
*         > Modified to not be version dependent anymore.
*         > Only create the number of CSVs required when a higher number
*           is specified in the control file.
*         > Support for Whitney, also support for G01 measure.
*         > Modified ENTITY-LENGTH to have a big buffer area.
*         > Trap non-existing input file and give out a message.
*
* 29APR97 IPM AAI - Guy Groulx.
*         > Fix for TPR 961009-1300-3333.  Arith overflow on measure file with
*             error 45.  Problem is really a measure problem, but this version
*             works around by declaring the measure file invalid.
*         > Fix problem with percentage linked/unlinked which were not being
*             reset for each CSV data file.
*         > MEASURE-TABLE now contains the external file name.
*         > Added Neveda numbers.
*         > ALLOW "G" as valid Guardian-type.
*
* 13Aug98 IPM AAJ - Guy Groulx.
*         > Fix for Whitney type.   8, 0 is actually what was released.
*         > Proper fix for DISK entries.   Use READ-QBUSY-TIME and
*           WRITE-QBUSY-TIME when available.
*         > Do not validate CPU type, subtype if CONVERTTO is not used.
*         > Eventhough MeasTCM was YEAR 2000 compliant, removed call to ACCEPT
*           from DATE and replaced with CURRENT-DATE.
*
* 23Nov98 IPM AAK - Guy Groulx.    Not yet released.
*         > Changed check for LCM >= 0 to > 0 so that div by 0 does not occur.
* 29Jun99 > Added NSR-T for S72000 cpus.   9,1 is the type, subtype.
*         > Will now have a buffer for new cpu types.
*         > DiskModel lines will now be written to CSV file.
*
* 04Nov01 IPM AAL
*         > Soln 10-001227-8157.
*           Added NSR-V for S74000 cpus. 9,2 is the type, subtype.
*           Added NSR-D for S7400 cpus.  9,10 is the type, subtype.
*         > Fix for Soln 10-000518-8168. Abnormal termination (error 87) with
*           record allocation error for large measure data files, when number
*           of CSVs created much less than the number possible. Added check for
*           counter overflow. Use 64-bit counters when 32-bit counters overflow.
*         > Fix for Soln 10-000602-8415. MeasTCM now correctly reports the NSK
*           version of the measured system in the CSV file. Earlier, it used
*           to report the MEASURE version of the data file.
*         > Fix for Soln 10-000925-0463. Inserted check for a blank volume
*           name in FILE-NAME of DISCOPEN-DEFINITION, to prevent Volume-Link
*           error.
*         > Fix for Soln 10-001222-8124. Blank spaces before the keywords in
*           the Control file are now ignored.
*         > Fix for Soln 10-001226-8148. Incorrect write activity was being
*           reported as the value of Volume-read-busy-time used to change
*           before computation of Volume-write-busy-time.
*         > Fix for Soln 10-010627-1347. Support for Virtual Disks.
*         > Fix for Soln 10-011016-3820.  MeasTCM Abends with Cobol85 Library
*           Error 121, Arithmetic overflow, when a Measure data file contains
*           more than 16383 PROCESS records.
*
* 10Jan03 SPR AAM
*         > Soln 10-021028-2764.
*           CSV files not created on G06.17 and G06.18 giving
*           error in purging CSV file.
*
* 25Jul03 SPR AAN
*         > Soln 10-030328-5170.
*           MEASTCM: Arithmetic overflow at MEASTCM-AAM.#7111(SOURCE1).
*           W08 and W08 size is changed to 9(15).9(3).
*           W13 and W14 size is changed to 9(15).
*           W03, W04, W06 and W07 size is changed to 9(10).
*           CSV-FILE-RECORD size changed to 172.
*         > Soln 10-030429-5986.
*           MEASTCM: arithmetic overflow #T6042D40-10JAN03-MEASTCM-AAM.#7108.
*         > Soln 10-030502-6113.
*           MEASTCM: Arithmetic overflow at T6042AAM.#7114.
*         > Soln 10-020717-0465.
*           Meastcm cannot support 76K and 86K CPU factors having power-values
*           > 99.99.
*
* 21Nov03 SPR AAO
*         > Soln 10-020415-8203.
*           DISKCONVERTTO, ACTUALDISK42, ACTUALDISK43,  ACTUALDISK44,DISKFACTOR
*           keywords are introduced, which enables disk scaling.
*
* 09JUL04 SPR AAP
*         > Soln 10-040510-5889.
*           Measure Data File from a mixed Disk System now displays
*           the correct number of disks.
*
* 01MAY05 T6042H01
*         > An IPV(Initial Product Version) Release, MeasTCM (T6042 H01)
*           has been enhanced to support the new MEASURE YOSEMITE External
*           Record Format. New ZMS-<Entity>-Definitions for the Entities
*           CPU, DISC, PROCESS, DISCOPEN have been added to the COPYLIB File
*           to access YOSEMITE Entity Records.
*           New Procedures have been added to SOURCE1 File for
*           supporting YOSEMITE.
*           Support to NSE-A CPU.
*           Support to JBOD Disks(BF07255B2C,BF0725754B,BF07258243,BF14658244).
*           Support to FCSA (Fibre Channel ServerNet Adapter).
*
* 01MAY06 T6042AAQ
*         > Soln 10-060403-5541.
*           MeasTCM now supports NSR-Z(S88000) and NSR-H(S78000) processors,
*           and generates CSV files with correct CPU time with CONVERTTO NSE-A
*           directive.
*
* 24MAY06 T6042AAR
*         > Soln 10-060505-6280.
*           The Interrupt processes busy time is no more accounted in the
*           CPU-BUSY-TIME of the System cateagory.
* 1SEP06  T6042AAS
*         > Soln 10-060830-8685
*           Added NSE-P for NS1000 cpus. 10,0 is the type, subtype.
*           Added NSE-D for NS14000 cpus.10,2 is the type, subtype.
* 2JAN07  T6042AAU
*         > Soln 10-060926-9325.
*           Support for the JBOD discs(BF07255B2C,BF0725754B,BF07258243,BF14658244).
*           Support to FCSA (Fibre Channel ServerNet Adapter).
*           Support for 46144 disc.
*           Support for 4638 disc.
*           Support for NSR-Z(S88000) and NSR-H(S78000) processors.
*
*         > Soln 10-061115-0524.
*           The Disk scaling workflow in MeasTCM has been modified to treat
*           the scaling of each disk individually. Unlike the previous approach,
*           the disk measurements( read-busy-time, write-busy-time, etc.) are now
*           scaled before being populated in the arrays( like volume-read-busy-time,
*           volume-write-busy-time, etc.). Thus, the inaccuracy which arises out of
*           cumulative addition of disk-power-value has been done away with.
*           The Physical disk reads and writes have been made non scalable.
* 2MAY08  T6042AAW
*         > Soln 10-080208-0419
*           Added NSE-Q for NS1200 cpus. 10,91 is the type, subtype.
*           Added NSE-T for NS16200 cpus. 10,83 is the type, subtype.
* 19APR10 T6042AAZ
*         > Soln 10-100304-8526
*           Support for H02,H03,H04,H05 version of measure files are added.
*           Added NSE-T and NSE-Q CPUs to Table of CPU-types.
*           Modified 'H-CPU-NUM' for available number of H-CPUs.
* 30AUG10 T6042ABA
*         > Added  support for J-Series Blades.
*         > Added NSE-M for NB50000 cpus. 10,71 is the type, subtype.
* 10NOV10 T6042ABA
*         > Soln 10-080623-4041
*         > Modified paragraph 3510-READ-DISCOPEN-TOTALS-CONT,3515-TREAT-DISCOPEN-T-INFO
*         > to read individual discopen entities to get virtual disk read/write time.
*         > Added paragraph 3411-TREAT-DISCOPEN-T-ENTITY
*         > Added paragraphs 3520-VOLUME-DOPN-UPDAT,3520-VOLUME-DOPN-UPDAT-Y with binary search
*         > to accomodate virtual disks for SMF.
* 23NOV10 T6042ABA
*         > Soln 10-090116-8480
*         > No more zero values for disc read/write counts in csv file.
* 23NOV10 T6042ABA
*         > Added support for latest JBOD disks.
* 29NOV11 T6042ABC
*         >Capacity Enhancements Program
*         >Added support for NSR-E,NSR-J,NSE-K,NSE-I,NSE-S and NSE-B CPUs.
*         >Removed old C-series and D-series CPUs.
*         >Added support for multi-core CPUs-NSE-M,NSE-W,NSE-AD and NSE-AB.
*         >Added support for SAS disks (subtype 51).
*         >Added support for Write Cache feature for SAS disks.
*         >Added partial support for XP disk configurations-XP24KRG5A and XP24KRG5B
*         >Added support for H06 version of Measure.
*         >Added support for CLIM controller.
*         >Modified the disk algorithm to include read ans write seek times to calculate diskspeedup.
*         >Added a new keyword NUMTMFTRAILS to support multiple auxilary TMF audit trails.
*         >As object file reached maximum possible size, disk related paragraphs are moved
*         >into sub program "SPDISKINFO" and Eroorhandling/termination routines are
*         >moved into sub program "SPCOMPLETION".
*****************************************************************************
*
* Index to paragraphs - (only major paragraphs included here)
*
*      100-ENTRY.                          Main control.
*      1000-INITIALIZE.                    Initialization.
*      2000-CONTROL-FILE-PROCESSING.       Process control file.
*      2400-MEASURE-TABLE-SCAN.            Validate Measure files.
*
*      3000-CORE-PROCESSING.               Main loop.
*      3100-READ-CPU-INFO.                 Read CPU data and process.
*      3200-READ-DISC-INFO.                Read DISC data and process.
*      3300-READ-PROCESS-INFO.             Read PROCESS data and process.
*      3400-READ-DISCOPEN-INFO.            Read DISCOPEN data and process.
*
*      4000-PRINT-REPORT.                  Produce audit reports.
*      5000-CLOSE-MEASDATA.                Close Measure files.
*      6000-WRITE-CSV.                     Write CSV file.
*      7000-DISPLAY-SUMMARY.               Display run statistics.
*      9000-COMPLETION.                    Shutdown processing.
*      9980-COMPUTE-INTR-AUX.              To find the cpu busy time of prior  ity 255 processes.
*      9990-ADD-AUX-TO-CAT.                Modify the cpu busy counter of $    system cateagory.
